\f2\i0\b\fs36 \cf2 \outl0\strokewidth0 Welcome to the Mediumocracy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 Social media abhors expertise. Not by design\'97no one held a meeting and decided that\'97but by structure. Yuval Noah Harari's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amazon.com/Nexus-Brief-History-Information-Networks/dp/0593731565"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Nexus}} makes the mechanism clear: information networks become dangerous when they optimize for speed and reach rather than truth-testing. Truth is 
\f1\i expensive
\f0\i0  in work sense. (Or it should be if you want to 
\f1\i trust
\f0\i0  the information; another reason large language model {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://technologyandsociety.org/whats-it-like-to-trust-an-llm-the-devolution-of-trust-psychology/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 aren't all that}}.) Peer review, professional licensing, regulatory oversight\'97all of it exists to stress-test claims against each other, to build in friction, to make it hard to be catastrophically wrong without someone in an adjacent office noticing. That process is slow and annoying and occasionally captured by the wrong people. It is also the only mechanism humanity has developed that reliably separates what is true from what merely 
\f1\i feels
\f0\i0  true. You know, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truthiness"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 truthiness}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32 \cf2 The short-form internet nuked all of that.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 It's not just that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://nctasocial.com/how-misinformation-spreads-faster-than-truth-on-social-media/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 misinformation spreads faster than truth}}\'97it does, reliably, at scale, across every platform studied. A deeper effect is structural. A celebrity with a large following has a 
\f1\i direct pipe
\f0\i0  to millions of people with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.perplexity.ai/search/what-is-the-longest-truth-soci-PlsHuhv.R0WZPbnY6d1tgQ"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 no editors}}, no peer reviewers, no departmental colleagues, no obligation whatsoever to update when the evidence changes. They are in front of the classroom and the whiteboard\'97as we've {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://banapana.com/2026/03/doomtubers"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 noted elsewhere}}\'97but have none of the institutional scaffolding that made the classroom trustworthy.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32 \cf2 The intimacy of the medium is the con.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 When someone looks you in the eye through a phone screen and delivers a confident take on vaccine safety or epidemiology or the mechanics of government, the brain {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyberpsychology.eu/article/view/4285"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 registers that as conversation}}. It is not conversation. It is broadcast dressed up in intimacy's clothes. Celebrity compresses all of that institutional friction into a single node. One voice. One vibe. The authority signals survive intact. The accountability structures do not.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32 \cf2 The Warm-Up Act\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 Celebrity has always nudged at the edges of governance. Ronald Reagan spent years in California politics before the White House. Jesse Ventura had {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesse_Ventura"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 a colorful and arguably coherent political identity}} before becoming governor of Minnesota. These were exceptions, and the guardrails held\'97not because the system was wise, but because the 
\f1\i media environment
\f0\i0  hadn't yet selected hard against expertise.\
Dr. Oz arrived as a transitional figure\'97a celebrity adjacent to expertise and fame (via Oprah), borrowing the authority of a medical credential while systematically hollowing it out.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa300\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Quick rule of thumb: if a doctor in an advertisement is 
\f1\i charging you
\f0\i0  for health information, it's a scam. Not probably a scam. A scam. The AMA's code of ethics holds that a physician's primary obligation is to the patient, and that financial incentives shouldn't distort clinical judgment. Even if they are selling you something that works, profit comes before 
\f1\i you
\f0\i0 . The medical industry {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://usrtk.org/healthwire/billions-in-drug-and-medical-device-company-payments-to-medical-professionals/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 is awash in this problem}} right now.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Gwyneth Paltrow built a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://goop.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 wellness empire}} on the aesthetic of expertise\'97the clean lines, the authoritative tone, the implication that she had access to knowledge your actual doctor didn't. Jenny McCarthy prosecuted a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jenny_McCarthy%23Autism_and_vaccines"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 years-long campaign}} against childhood vaccination with no medical training whatsoever. Measles is now {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/measles-is-making-a-comeback-can-we-stop-it-202503063091"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 making a comeback}}.\
Meanwhile, in November 2014, a sixteen-year-old named Jaden Smith sat down with the 
\f1\i New York Times
\f0\i0  to share his views on education. 
\f1\i "You never learn anything in school,"
\f0\i0  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://archive.nytimes.com/tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/jaden-willow/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 he explained}}, having never attended one. The clip went viral. Educators were furious\'97it landed on the desk of the National Dropout Prevention Center with enough force to rattle the furniture. But the fury missed the real question: 
\f1\i why was a sixteen-year-old with no experience of ordinary school given a national platform to pronounce on education in the first place?
\f0\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The answer is: his father is Will Smith. That's the whole answer. And the medium didn't care.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32 \cf2 Look, Not All Famous People Are Idiots\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 Let's get something out of the way, because it matters to the argument.\
This is not a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/ng-interactive/2024/sep/10/athletes-political-views-election-sports"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 shut-up-and-dribble piece}}. The argument that famous people should stay in their lane and leave governance to the professionals is a little too convenient. Intelligence is roughly a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 normal distribution}} across all human populations, including famous ones. Hedy Lamarr {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hedy_Lamarr"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 invented the frequency-hopping technology}} that became the foundation of WiFi and Bluetooth\'97and the U.S. Navy ignored her patent for decades because she was a movie star. Mayim Bialik plays a neuroscientist on television and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayim_Bialik"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 has a Ph.D. in neuroscience}} from UCLA\'97which means she is, technically, more qualified than the show. Milla Jovovich recently co-built {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 MemPalace}}, currently the highest-benchmarking open-source AI memory system available. There is room in this world for geniuses, and they show up in unexpected places.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 Most people, however, are not geniuses. That's not an insult. That's what the word means. Do we, as an audience, filter our fact-finding on the Internet accordingly?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf2 The problem isn't that celebrities are stupid. The problem is that becoming famous is a full-time job. A career in media\'97building an audience, maintaining a public presence, staying relevant\'97consumes exactly the kind of time that expertise also requires. Malcolm Gladwell's famous {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amazon.com/Outliers-Story-Success-Malcolm-Gladwell/dp/0316017930"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 10,000-hour threshold}} was already a simplification of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.amazon.com/Peak-Secrets-New-Science-Expertise/dp/0544947223"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Anders Ericsson's research}} on deliberate practice\'97and even Ericsson's number is a floor, not a finish line. Genuine domain expertise in law, epidemiology, military doctrine, or intelligence operations runs orders of magnitude higher, and the hours have to be the right kind of hard. Hours spent becoming a household name are hours 
\f1\i not
\f0\i0  spent understanding how infectious disease spreads, or how a defense budget works, or what the CIA actually does. The math is simple and it is brutal and social media seeps right through the cracks in knowledge gathering like an acid.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 So when we put celebrities in charge of things that require expertise, we are not making a mistake about individual people. We are making a categorical error. We are confusing the signal\'97fame, broadcast reach, the quality of being-known\'97with the substance. And here's the thing: we didn't arrive at that confusion by accident. We were trained into it.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf2 The Trust Collapse and the Vacuum It Left\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa540\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 And the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.pewresearch.org/science/2023/11/14/americans-trust-in-scientists-positive-views-of-science-continue-to-decline/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 numbers bear this out}}. The share of Americans expressing the strongest level of trust in scientists fell from 39% in 2020 to 23% by late 2023. Among Republicans, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2023/11/14/health/trust-in-science-pew-survey/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 nearly 40% said they had little or no confidence}} in scientists to act in the public interest\'97up from 14% at the start of the pandemic. Trust in the FDA and state public health officials {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.kff.org/health-information-trust/kff-tracking-poll-on-health-information-and-trust-january-2025/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 each dropped by double digits}}. Trust in the federal government to do the right thing\'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.pew.org/en/trust/archive/fall-2024/americans-deepening-mistrust-of-institutions"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 22% as of spring 2024}}, near a sixty-year low. Is it people developing mistrust or mistakenly believing they and their celebrity priests know better than experts?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf2 The Apprentice Was the Training Data\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 There's a phenomenon researchers call {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://nij.ojp.gov/topics/articles/csi-effect-does-it-really-exist"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 the CSI Effect}}: two decades of forensic procedural television convinced a significant portion of the American public that real police work resembles what happens on 
\f1\i CSI
\f0\i0 \'97instantaneous DNA results, infallible forensic scientists, cases solved in forty-two minutes plus commercials. Jurors began demanding evidence that doesn't exist in real crime scenes, because television had trained them to expect it. The medium didn't just carry the content. It shaped what the audience believed was normal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f1\i \cf2 The Apprentice
\f0\i0  ran the same operation on executive competence.\
For fourteen seasons, Donald Trump performed the aesthetic of decisive leadership\'97the boardroom, the firing, the theatrical certainty that the right answer was always obvious and he always had it. This is not a coincidence to be noted and moved past. This is the mechanism. The show didn't just make Trump famous. It trained millions of viewers to recognize what executive authority was supposed to look like. And what it was supposed to look like was 
\f1\i him
\f0\i0 .\
But here's what makes this more than a story about one television show\'97or one man. Simultaneously, social media and short-form content were rewriting the selection pressures for public attention across every domain. The traits that make someone successful on these platforms\'97parasocial intimacy, emotional legibility, charisma at scale, the ability to hold attention in under sixty seconds\'97became the same traits that make someone politically viable. The environment didn't just 
\f1\i allow
\f0\i0  celebrity to migrate into governance. It 
\f1\i selected
\f0\i0  for it. Evolution doesn't have intentions. It just rewards what survives.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa540\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marshall_McLuhan"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 McLuhan}} would have recognized this without blinking. The medium isn't just the message\'97it's the hiring committee. When the primary medium of public life became one that rewards performed authenticity over demonstrated competence, performed authenticity was what got hired. We didn't decide to elect celebrities. We built an environment that made celebrities the fittest organisms, and then we held an election.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf2 The Ledger\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 Let's look at what we've actually done.\
Pete Hegseth\'97Fox News host, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Hegseth"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Secretary of Defense}}. Robert F. Kennedy Jr.\'97anti-vaccine activist, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_F._Kennedy_Jr."}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Secretary of Health and Human Services}}. Kash Patel\'97{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kash_Patel"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 author of a children's book about the "Deep State,"}} Director of the FBI. Jeanine Pirro\'97Fox News judge, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeanine_Pirro"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 U.S. Attorney for Washington D.C.}}. Linda McMahon\'97WWE CEO, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linda_McMahon"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Secretary of Education}}. Kari Lake\'97television news anchor, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kari_Lake"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Director of Voice of America}}. Elon Musk\'97owner of a social media platform, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Department_of_Government_Efficiency"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 informal co-head of an advisory body}} with real authority over federal agencies.\
This is not a rant. It's a ledger. What each of these roles actually requires\'97expertise in military operations, epidemiology, intelligence tradecraft, federal law, education policy, international broadcasting, government efficiency\'97is not what each of these people has demonstrably 40k+ hours doing. The gap is not a matter of opinion. It is a matter of time and arithmetic.\
And then there's Kristi Noem, who is a slightly different case\'97not a celebrity appointed to govern, but a politician who learned to perform celebrity so completely that she forgot which one was the job. As Secretary of Homeland Security she conducted {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.thedailybeast.com/ice-barbie-trolled-by-lawmakers-over-many-costume-changes/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 ICE raids in full makeup and a bulletproof vest}}, then drove straight to Fox News in a different outfit. She piloted a Coast Guard vessel. She rode a horse at Mount Rushmore for a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.thedailybeast.com/all-of-ice-barbie-kristi-noems-most-heinous-outfits/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 $220 million DHS advertisement}}. A congressional Democrat thanked her for finding time "among your many photo ops and costume changes to testify." She lasted fourteen months. The medium had colonized the mission so thoroughly that the mission disappeared.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 To be clear, this is not a left-right issue. Gavin Newsome has been having {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://x.com/GavinNewsom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 a lot of fun on Twitter}}. Zohran Mamdani is praised for his {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wired.com/story/the-big-interview-podcast-zohran-mamdani/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 mastery of social media}}. Left or right, it's clear that Joe Rogan, Bill Maher, and\'97I can't dignify this celebrity with a name check, call her What's-Her-Butt\'97are currently more influential with the President than most lobbyists or policy advisors. Not because they got smarter. Because the room got noisier and they have the biggest speakers. Even the President is an audience member who does not understand the value of expertise.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf2 What Is Parasocial Loyalty But Royalty?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 Here's the thing that should unsettle you: none of this is new. What we're calling the celebocracy or the mediaocracy or what I'm calling the mediumocracy, or the Barnum administration, pick your term\'97is not a collapse into something strange. It is a collapse 
\f1\i backward
\f0\i0  into something very, very old.\
Monarchy ran on exactly this dynamic. Millions of people with a profound, one-sided emotional investment in someone they would never meet, whose decisions shaped their lives, who owed them nothing in return. The peasants knew everything about the king's court\'97the intrigues, the exploits, the fashions, the feuds\'97and the king knew nothing about them except that they existed in aggregate and could be taxed. Parasocial relationships didn't begin with YouTube. They began with divine right.\
Celebrity culture didn't invent this structure, but social media let them industrialize it. And then the internet 
\f1\i personalized
\f0\i0  it\'97gave it the illusion of two-way contact, the feeling of intimacy, the parasocial warmth of being-known-by. At least with royalty, the asymmetry was legible. The celebrity looks you in the eye through the screen and says 
\f1\i we
\f0\i0 . Joe Rogan doesn't have subjects. He has 
\f1\i listeners
\f0\i0 . That's the upgrade. That's also the con.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa540\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The meritocracy experiment\'97credentials, peer review, institutional vetting, the slow expensive apparatus for stress-testing whether someone actually knows what they claim to know\'97was the interruption. The anomaly in the historical record. We built it because the alternative, which is rule by whoever commands the most intense one-sided devotion, had a documented track record of spectacular failure. We are now, methodically, dismantling out experiment. Not because anyone decided to. Because the medium selected for it.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf2 This Too Shall Pass. Slowly.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs20 \cf2 P.T. Barnum called in the freaks, and the crowds came. They always do, for a while. There is a reason Barnum is not remembered as a statesman.\
Movements like #{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.resistandunsubscribe.com"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 ResistAndUnsubscribe}} are natural reactions to performative incompetence\'97people instinctively withdrawing attention from systems they've recognized as extractive. These movements are real. They are also, themselves, fads, subject to the same attention dynamics they're reacting against. Popular resistance to celebrity governance, organized on the platforms that created celebrity governance, does not escape the medium.\
The tide will change. Not because people will suddenly come to their senses, but because the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FTC_v._Meta_Platforms"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 regulatory and legal environment around the platforms is shifting}}. Courts have begun {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://apnews.com/article/meta-youtube-social-media-addiction-d04fe8f7d410f943aa2a8e443c4eb1e1"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 finding against Meta and YouTube}} in ways that suggest the environment that created this selection pressure may itself be subject to selection pressure. The landscape changes slowly, then quickly. The institutions that were built to interrupt the last version of this problem are still here, battered and underfunded and occasionally captured by the wrong people, but still here.\
The medium created the mediumocracy. Changing the medium is the only repair that works. Everything else {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.glam.com/1879262/krist-noem-inappropriate-cosplay-outfits/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 is a costume change}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl24\slmult1\sa300\partightenfactor0
